segments.text: The Chevrolet Motor Division had a representative that would visit all the dealers, General Motors dealers, and he would check or spot check the defective parts and the forms that were necessary, and he'd put his name on there and okay it.
And I said, well, hell, I can do that.
They had a representative that came down from Chevrolet Motor Division.
His name was Sam O. Smith, SOS.
And some of those guys there, they chased that same old, you know, four-letter word.
And he was a nice chap.
He talked to the people working in the parts department and everything.
So I put him over to the side and I said,
I'd like to have a job like this fellow's got that checks out these defective points.
Like, you know, I've been here a long time, and I know that.
And he says, yeah, I can understand that, but it's the policy with General Motors that we have somebody like that that has a traveling job.
He's got to be a college graduate.
I said, well.
Why does it have to be a college graduate?
He says, well, I don't need to know.
I said, but that's the policy.
And we won't consider anybody unless they got a college degree.
I said, well, I guess I'll have to get a college degree if I want to get a job that is worthwhile.
And that's what got me started, wanting to get me a college degree.
And then the two of my wife's brothers who were coming over, who were attending A&M, my wife told them about my conversation with Sam O. Smith.
And so they encouraged me.
They said, well, if you're going to go to college, come to A&M.
A&M will give what you need, and if you've got the ability, you've got the know-how, you can make it.
And the degree from A&M is worth a lot.
It's recognized.
I said, well, that's what I'll do.
So, I told, I told Rachel about it, and she agreed, and that's where I started there.
Did, did anyone discourage you?
Was there anyone that?
Well, yeah.
Well, there was this parts manager.
I was making $300 a month.
At that time, it was a good trade.
And I had a position in back of the parts department facing the shop.
And I wasn't waiting on the general trade.
I was a mechanics parts man.
I waited on them because before, the mechanic would have to go out to the front and wait in line, you know, until you got to it.
And the boss didn't like that.
He says, these mechanics, they got to make a living.
They can't be out there wasting their time waiting.
We need a man in the back window.
And that was my job.
So I told my boss that I wanted to go to college and I needed to take two summer courses.
And he was very nice.
He let me go to class in the morning and get back over there and work in my back window.
And so I was offered a raise if I would forget paying him.
He says, we'll pay you $400 a month if you stay.
And $400 a month at that time was good pay, see?
And I turned it down.
And I said, oh.
He was very disappointed.
I said, okay, okay, good luck.
And we were pretty good friends.
All right, so with the G.I.
Bill then, you came up here to visit A&M.
Do you remember who you talked to?
Did you talk to Mr. Heaton?
No, it was another man.
Another man who was a tall, slender fellow.
He wasn't a registrar.
It was somebody else that was reviewing
on the scripts from these people.
And he was the one that told me, he says, you need to brush up on chemistry and math.
And that's about it.
I said, OK.
So you went back to take those at San Antonio College?
San Antonio Junior College, yes, sir.
And so I got that ready, got that put away.
And then I had to take this test.
All the students who were coming to A&M, especially the veterans, they had to take this test.
And it was supposed to be the equivalent to the test given all freshmen at Ohio State University.
It says, if you can pass that test, they're not telling us whether you're going to be able to do the work or not.
I took it and I passed it.
Then I had to go to the Veterans Administration and tell them, hey, the skids are greased.
Wait a minute.
You got to take a test over here.
Another one, see.
Similar to this one.
Well, I passed that one, too.
Then they went ahead and gave you the green light or something.
All right.
And then you came up here looking for housing.
Oh, yes.
And couldn't find anything?
No.
Oh, there was a, it was a college then.
The college didn't have those facilities, see.
And then all these veterans started coming in.
And, boy, they were coming from everywhere.
And so there was a project.
They were building this village right next to the car field.
And it had a sign on there that it was being built for the veterans, returning veterans.
And it was portable barracks.
And they put a wall in the middle and set up for two families.
They furnished a refrigerator, a cooking stove,
two beds, and all in a line.
But you couldn't get one of those at first?
When you first- No, no, no.
What was your wife's feeling about your leaving your job and going back to college?
She was all for it.
She knew that this was, it was more education for me.
And it would help me.
And her father, Rachel's father, believed in education because he came from Mexico, and the school facilities there were nonexistent.
And he knew that if you didn't have an education, all you could be was a cotton picker, say, or a grave digger.
And he stressed education to his 14 children.
before they all got a college education.
So my wife says, I haven't got all my education, but I want it and I want to get it some way.
And so she encouraged me to go.
So you came up here in the fall of 1949?
Yes.
And how did you, did you drive up in your car?
Yes.
What did you bring with you?
What kind of belongings?
What clothing and everything?
Well, there wasn't much to talk about.
I had just regular civilian clothes and I, there was at the time, first of all they didn't have the room, you know.
And secondly, I was always harassing the freshmen at the annex or at the Brown Air Force Base.
a great number of vacant military barracks.
And that's where we were at.
Now they had all the veterans in one area, and all the regular high school kids had just got out in another area, and the band had another area.
About how many veterans were there?
Well, there was about three.
three barracks and there was about ten, twenty, there must have been about between forty and fifty veterans.
Right.
And did you all live in bunks or did you have separate rooms?
No, no.
There was no?
No, we had what do you call them?

upper no yeah two bucks did you veterans chuckle that this was like going back to the war uh because you'd been through no it was a matter of fact uh they didn't like to discuss it you know and uh so we never talked about it you know we just had to study and there was no uh
No time to shoot the bull.
Did you, did you wear uniforms?
No.
Or you veterans wore civilian clothes?
That's right.
They figured that we had already served.
But, but I wanted to wear, I wanted to get into the Corps of Cadets.
And at that time, they wanted students to get into the Corps and then eventually get their commission as second lieutenants.
Well, I never dreamed of that.
I just wanted to be in the Corps, and I wanted to wear boots in my senior year.
So I went to see Colonel Volkner, Hayden L. Volkner.
I says, Colonel, I like the Corps, and I'd like to get in.
Well, he says, how old are you?
I don't think it would get you in.
See, he was thinking of the commission.
I wasn't.
But I was too dumb to tell him, I don't want no commission.
I just want to be in the Corps.
He says, we're going to Fourth Army.
I want to get, see if I can get you a waiver.
Well, about a couple of weeks later, he said, nope.
Go see Colonel Boat.
And he says, I'm sorry, but
I've got a response to my letter, and it says that it would not be in the best interest of the Army.
I'm sorry.
So I thanked him and went out.
And then there was some guys from Mexico, and they were in the band.
And since they were Mexican citizens, they couldn't qualify for commissions.
How the hell did you get into the court?"
I said, no, we're not in the court, we're in the band.
And then we get to wear the uniform.
I said, I wish I had known how to play an instrument or something.
So they were in the court, so to speak, by being in the band and playing an instrument.
And I noticed there were students from just about everywhere.
I mean, foreign countries.
And there was, I remember the people from India, they had the wives, you know, and they, you know, of course there were, what do you call it?
I don't know, that little dot on their forehead.
It's a dot.
Okay.
And so we befriended a couple of those fellas.
And there were students majoring in some form of agriculture.
Now, what did you plan to major in when you got here?
I was going to go take agronomy.
Agronomy?
Agronomy, none of the husbandry.
And what were you planning, what were you dreaming of doing when you graduated?
Well, either work for A&M,
or be placed in one of these experimental stations.
Because you didn't plan to be a rancher yourself.
No, no, no, no.
I had no ranching experience.
Describe the route.
As you move in, did anybody attempt to haze you veterans?
No.
They left you all alone?
No, as a matter of fact,
As a matter of fact, I befriended all those freshman cadets.
And some of them would like to take off on like a Saturday night or Sunday and tank up on beer.
They had to get across the bridge, remember?
Worcester Bridge?
And they'd say, hey, Gunsy, you don't drink deal.
I said, no, I don't drink deal.
listen, you want to go out and will you drive us back?
Yeah.
So I got in with them, see?
And it was then that I learned that they kept these old quizzes in those little apple boxes, see?
So I had access to those, see?
That's a pretty good swamp.
That was a good swamp, see?
So whenever we were going, we were having, let's take American history.
have an A quiz.
Well we don't know what the Pope's going to ask.
And I forget the professor's name.
And they had them by names you see.
This is the test that this professor.
So we reviewed them.
And we'd get together at the table somewhere and we'd mention these things.
Well he's going to ask this.
He said this, he's going to ask that.
And we were ready, you see, for when the time came to go to class.
And he would pass the forms out, and we were ready for them.
Describe class day.
What time did you all get up?
What did you do?
Describe the whole day.
Was there a Reveille bugle that woke you up?
No.
No, we had alarm clocks.
I'm talking about the annex.
We had an alarm clock.
And I don't remember, I'm talking about the veterans.
Now they had a church of quarters or somebody over there in the, the other regular students,
that would cause them to get up early and so forth.
But over here with the veterans, we just had our alarm clocks.
And let's see, you had a gang shower?
A what?
A gang shower.
You didn't have a private shower.
Oh, yeah, yeah, a gang shower, yeah.
And we had a row of commodes.
You remember those pot crackers?
whistle, you got a name for it but I won't give it to you, you know.
And here we're sitting on the stool, you know, and some ugly guy had the light running through him.
Oh, I tell you it was something.
Who did that?
I don't know.
And yes, we had regular
All right, so you'd get up, eat breakfast, then go to class, and you had class all morning.
Yes.
What did you all do in the afternoons?
Study.
Where did you study?
Either there or they had a place, a barracks, where it was called study hall.
But now you didn't have any private room.
Oh, no.
Nothing was private.
And you hung your, where did you hang your clothes?
Well, we had a laundry, see, and we sent it out.
But did you have a locker to hang your clothes in as a kind of a closet?
No, it was just a rack.
Oh, okay.
And a pipe going through and hangers.
But it wasn't closed up so you couldn't lock it?
No, we had a footlocker that you could, we had a padlock.
Then at night, where did y'all study?
In the same place, same study hall.
And what did you and your friends do if you wanted to relax at night?
Where did you go for a good time?
Well, there wasn't a good time.
It would be either down to Bryan or Caldwell.
And what would you all do in Caldwell?
Well, it was wide open.
And they just did about anything.
But they stayed together.
And they would go from one tavern to another.
Did you make some good friends that year?
Oh, yes.
Give some examples of the friendship that you all enjoyed.
there was this student who was Jewish, and his name was Dennerstein.
He was from Houston.
And I think his mother had a photo shop, and they had a lot of picture frames and all this.
And I remember when we were
or the freshmen, they would be given a little booklet with some ticket stubs.
That was a stub you had to turn in to get into the mess hall to eat.
So, there was some people that didn't want to go eat in the mess hall, and they'd go to a little snack bar that was there, and give them tickets.
And on Thursdays we had liver.
I'd be sitting next to the dentist and he'd say, I do.
Are you going to eat your liver?
No.
He'd get it for anybody else without a fart.
And he had three or four big chunks of liver.
I'll never forget that.
And when he'd go on leave, go home to visit, he'd come back to his barracks.
and somebody had already taken his mattress out and hid it somewhere.
Just pranks, you know.
So we were good friends.
Then there was Martin Cain.
He was from, what was it, I think it was Blue Shoe, Texas.
And they had gone out on a binge on it, and they got drunk.
And after it was over,
one of the girls was found to be pregnant.
And she said it was Martin Kane.
And Martin says, hey, it wasn't me.
I was passed out.
And so the gross father found out about it.
And then he came over there to the annex with two guys.
I think they were brothers.
And they went in the barracks and took Martin Kane.
by force.
And it took them a long time to get her married.
Oh, brother.
So then, I don't know, the military department got wind of it.
I don't know what they did.
It was too late.
It was fixed already.
But the girl said, I don't want nothing.
I just want to give the baby a name.
was already scheduled.
I say scheduled.
He was going to marry a girl already.
And good night.
The girl found out about what had happened, and that wedding was just below proportion.
And he finished his first year, but he didn't come back the second year.
So he disappeared.
The last I heard, he went out with a close friend of his that was a driller.
But he didn't drill for oil.
He drilled for water wells.
I don't know, whatever.
And then, let me see, he was born in King, and...
I'm just about to...
There were the Casa twins.
They were from Laredo.
Casa?
Caso.
Caso.
C-A-S-S-O.
And their parents had a wholesale grocery business.
You know, they had a big warehouse, and they would supply their grocery.
And they were twins.
And they were always doing something out of the ordinary.
And they'd get drowned out.
You know what I mean?
Okay.
And I'll never forget that.
We were friends, you know, but not close.
Then there was Organdigie from Laredo.
And his daddy had a wholesale oil operation.
He was a dealer, and he supplied service stations with oil.
And so, we weren't trouble.
Good friends, and that's... Did those young Aggie freshmen right out of high school ever turn to you older guys for advice?
No.
Not me anyway.
So you veterans kind of stuck together, and who were some of the teachers, counselors from that first year that you remember?
Well, it was Boss Hamilton.
Dirty shirt Nelson.
Screaming owl.
Screaming owl Nelson.
Oh, let me see.
Oh, gosh.
Did you have Happy Harry Hearth in English?
No.
Harrison Hearth?
No.
This was a man.
Well, yeah.
I can't think of his name right now.
It escapes me.
What were the toughest courses that first year for you?
That first year, the toughest was math.
But you passed everything.
Yes.
Passed everything.
Oh, yeah.
How often did you go back home to San Antonio?
I didn't have a set.
Whenever the opportunity arose, I would go.
Usually, like every other weekend, and I'd leave like on Saturday afternoon and get back Sunday, Sunday night.
So I had to go Monday class.
Did you go to Aggie football games that freshman, that first year?
No.
So you didn't get involved in the...
I didn't get involved, no.
Was there a, let's see, a bonfire?
Did you help?
No.
That first year, no.
We were confined, to lack of a better word, to the annex.
And no silver taps?
No silver taps, no.
Not until my wife joined me later.
Then I would get a
a ticket or two to maybe go to one or two games and uh.
Right and so you did well that first year and then that that next summer what did you do in the summer of 1950?
Did you go back to work or?
Oh yeah.
Yes sir.
Yeah I had to build on that um yeah I've been
I had a wife and I had a little boy, and so.
Right, so then you came back here with your wife in the fall of 1950.
How did y'all locate, how were you able to get that apartment over in College View?
What did you have to go through to?
I didn't, I just, you know,

applied and uh they said uh we've got a place for you over there at the college view would you like that hey yeah it's very good what i'm living in over here so uh it was it was better and so you you brought her and how old was your youngster then oh he was uh
Close to five.
Okay.
And what furniture did you bring?
None.
None.
None.
Oh, it was furnished?
Yeah.
Oh.
Yeah, yeah.
You see, we had two beds.
We had a refrigerator.
We had a stove.
And there were showers in there, and so we, it was,
We didn't go for the sofas and fancy.
Just the bare necessities.
All right.
Did you sell your house in San Antonio?
Yes.
Yeah, I had bought a house, a small frame house in San Antonio, and got a bank loan, which was authorized by the VA, and it was at four percent interest.
Unheard of.
When you sold that house and came here, do you remember how much money you brought with you that second year?
No, I don't remember exactly how much.
I must have had about $400 or $500, something like that.
And the rent at College View was $30?
Yeah, $30 a month.
Did that include utilities?
Yes.
Yes.
All right, so you moved in.
How soon before you all made friends with your neighbors?
Almost immediately.
Everybody was friendly and everybody that was there was there for the same purpose that I was there.
Hey, we're in the same boat, so let's...
Describe some of them.
Because I'm assuming this was a very, in today's words, a diverse group of people.
Well, you could call it that.
We didn't pick the barracks.
We didn't pick the friends.
He says, you go to barracks number so-and-so, and you take apartment so-and-so, which is upstairs or downstairs.
So it just happened that the immediate friends there
their husbands were studying to be a doctor of veterinary medicine, vets.
And this building that when you're coming in and you turn around, used to be the U.S. Department of Agriculture, now it's got another name.
And there used to be one of those vet majors that was
He did janitor work in that building, and I wanted that job because he was ready to graduate.
Now I already had this plan, somebody else is going to have it.
And so these veterans, all they did was study.
They had no place.
And there was Louis Springer.
He was from Virginia.
I'll tell you about this.
Lewis Springer, Wallace Lawson, Everett Beach.
Yeah, Wallace Lawson, Houston, San Antonio, and Everett D. Besch.
That guy, he had a cubby hole in his apartment.
And he was there all the time, except when he was going to go eat or go to the bathroom.
He went there to study?
I went there to study.
